nd an A.M. He was licensed to preach the following June 1804, three years before his New Preston ordination."},{"number":4,"category":"career","header":"Conducted seminaries at Utica and Canandaigua New York","body":"After his Hartford Asylum tenure, Samuel and his wife Abigail Goodrich conducted 'large seminaries' at Utica and Canandaigua New York. While in Utica in 1832 Abigail began publishing The Mother's Magazine, the early American periodical of maternal Christian instruction she would edit for nearly two decades."}],"education":[{"institution":"Yale College","institution_id":"INST002","graduation_year":1803,"degree":"B.A.","honors":"Phi Beta Kappa; A.M."}],"slug":"samuel-whittlesey-1775"},"I00434":{"id":"I00434","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"bio":{"first_name":"Abigail","maiden_name":"Goodrich","married_names":["Whittlesey"],"gender":"female","display_name":"Abigail Goodrich Whittlesey","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1778349799/abilgailgwhittlesey-resized_miuoy8.png"},"birth":{"year":1788,"month":11,"day":29,"city":"Ridgefield","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1858,"month":7,"day":16},"residence":{},"burial":{},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":true,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{"father_research_notes":"Family of Goodrich (Ridgefield Conn.). Educated at Berlin Conn."},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"HD0102","date_year":1808,"date_month":11,"date_day":10,"location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","children_ids":["HD3790","HD3791","HD3792","HD3793","HD3794","HD3795","HD3796"]}],"education":[],"career":[],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["literature"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"literature","header":"Edited Mother's Magazine for nearly two decades","body":"Abigail began publishing 'The Mother's Magazine' in 1832 while in Utica New York, editing it until about 1850. She subsequently revived it under the title 'Magazine for Mothers,' running one of the earliest American periodicals devoted to maternal Christian instruction."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[],"research_sources":[{"bib_id":"BIB005","page":"Entry 360 (under Samuel Whittlesey, his wife)"}],"documents":[],"slug":"abigail-goodrich-1788"}},"burialCemetery":{"id":"CEM275","name":"Cave Hill Cemetery","city":"Louisville","county":"Jefferson","state":"Kentucky","country":"United States","founded":1848,"wikipedia_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cave_Hill_Cemetery","primary_url":"https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/73354/cave-hill-cemetery","hooker_connections":["HD3787","HD3849","HD3855","I00478","X02786","I00983","H02056"],"notes":"Major Louisville Kentucky cemetery (founded 1848). Henry Chandler Cowles (HD3787) and his wife Elizabeth Lucretia Waller Cowles (X02786) buried here. Henry Chandler was originally interred at Oak Woods Cemetery, Chicago in September 1939; his remains were transferred to Cave Hill in 1982 to rest beside Elizabeth (per Victor M. Cassidy, 'Henry Chandler Cowles, Pioneer Ecologist,' p. 346). The transfer reunited the family in Elizabeth's hometown.","person_ids":["HD3849","HD3855","I00478"]},"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}